&lt;p&gt;Contamination by microscopic plastic particles has become one of the foremost issues for the global environment. The SFB Microplastics at the University of Bayreuth involves more than 20 research groups to study the creation, the biological effects and the transport of microplastic in the environment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This project deals with the transport of microplastic particles in natural soils. Its goal is to understand the physical mechanics which drive or hinder the infiltration and the transport through the porous soil matrix. It will heavily use methods of computational fluid dynamics such as Lattice-Boltzmann, Immersed-Boundary and Volume-of-Fluid. Due to the large separation of length scales, the project is very challenging from a numerical point of view. In the framework of the research consortium Microplastics we will work closely with our experimental partners in Bayreuth and Cologne.&lt;br /&gt;
Roughly one third of the project will be concerned with developing an appropriate simulation code in C++. In the remaining two thirds, the student will carry out large-scale simulations on local, national and European supercomputer facilities.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The required supercomputer ressources will be provided by the local computing cluster available at the University of Bayreuth as well as by projects on national supercomputing systems such as SuperMUC (Garching) and JEWELS (J&amp;uuml;lich).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The successful candidate must possess a strong background in theoretical physics, computational mathematics/engineering, geosciences or a similar discipline. Good programming skills are required. A background in fluid mechanics is desirable, but not explicitly required. Research will be conducted in the Biofluid Simulation and Modeling group at the University of Bayreuth, Germany. Bayreuth is a medium-sized town with a fairly large student population and is situated in a beautiful natural setting between the mountains of the &amp;quot;Fr&amp;auml;nkische Schweiz&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;Fichtelgebirge&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;F&amp;uuml;r Bewerbungen oder weitere Informationen kontaktieren Sie bitte &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:stephan.gekle@uni-bayreuth.de&quot;&gt;stephan.gekle@uni-bayreuth.de&lt;/a&gt; oder besuchen Sie &lt;a href=&quot;http://biofluid.physik.uni-bayreuth.de&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;unsere Webseite&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.neurobiology-konstanz.com/foster&quot;&gt;Psychophysics of Polarization Vision&lt;/a&gt; group headed by &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.neurobiology-konstanz.com/team/james-foster&quot;&gt;James Foster&lt;/a&gt; is recruiting a doctoral student to study the remarkable polarization compass system in insects. We investigate how insects perceive and integrate visual information to navigate their environments. We approach these questions through a combination of environmental imaging, behavioural experiments and statistical modelling.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt; When the sun is hidden from view, foraging honeybees use an internal map of the pattern of polarized light across the sky to determine their current heading. Sensitivity to polarized skylight, while rare in vertebrates, is found in the eyes of a wide range of insect species. With their varied anatomies, these insects view the world with drastically different eyes. The consequences of these differences, for both perception and behaviour, remain poorly understood. Recent advances in environmental imaging of polarization, as well as 3D ocular anatomy and connectomics datasets, now make it possible to predict, describe and explain these differences.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As part of our team, the doctoral candidate will investigate the effects of eye design on the perception of polarized light under different sky conditions. Using full-sky polarization imaging to collect a dataset of real-world polarization patterns, they will simulate insect perception of natural skies as viewed through the ocular anatomies of different species. Computational models will be developed in close partnership with our network of collaborators, providing access to expertise from the fields of comparative anatomy, neurophysiology and biorobotics. The work will run in parallel with behavioural experiments conducted by other team members at the university&amp;rsquo;s honeybee facility, providing opportunities to test and refine model predictions. As part of an expanding group in the international environment at Konstanz University, this project will advance a new approach to the study of insect vision.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Requirements&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;bull; MSc in Biology, Neuroscience, Engineering or a related field.&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;bull; Proficiency in a programming language (R, Matlab, Python).&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;bull; A strong interest in Sensory Ecology.&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;bull; Experience in computational modelling or photography would be preferable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Start date:&lt;/strong&gt; in 2023, exact date flexible.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Applications should include a letter of motivation, CV, and the contact details for two references, and be sent to &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:james.foster@uni-konstanz.de&quot;&gt;james.foster@uni-konstanz.de&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

